  {
    "verifyText": {
      "id": "lf_help_0",
      "value": "This tool calculates rates of return, before and after taxes, for a taxable and tax-exempt bond. Rates of return are shown for two scenarios: holding the bond to maturity and selling before maturity."
    }
  },
  {
    "verifyText": {
      "id": "lf_help_1",
      "value": "Tax-exempt bonds generate a lower rate of return because the interest that they pay is generally exempt from federal (and sometimes state) income taxes. The yield on a taxable bond that is equivalent to the yield on a tax-exempt bond is called the taxable-equivalent yield."
    }
  },
  {
    "verifyText": {
      "id": "lf_help_2",
      "value": "Taxable-equivalent yield depends on the investor's income tax rate. For example, an investor in the 25% tax bracket that owns a tax-exempt bond that yields 5% would require a yield of 6.67% on a taxable bond in order to make the taxable bond equally attractive."
    }
  },
  {
    "verifyText": {
      "id": "lf_help_3",
      "value": "This tool assumes that the taxable bond is taxed using the regular federal and state taxes, i.e. it is treated as a corporate bond."
    }
  },
  {
    "verifyText": {
      "id": "lf_help_4",
      "value": "Depending on the types of bonds being compared, the taxes applied to coupon payments will vary."
    }
  },
